l> 652\n | website                  = {{url|http://www.jekabpils.lv/}}\n | footnotes                = \n}}\n'''J\u0113kabpils''' ({{audio|Lv-J\u0113kabpils.ogg|pronunciation}}; {{lang-de|Jakobstadt}}; {{lang-pl|Jakub\u00f3w}}) is a [[city]] in southeastern Latvia roughly halfway between [[Riga]] and [[Daugavpils]] and spanning the [[Daugava River]]. Historic J\u0113kabpils lies on the left bank, in [[Selonia]] while historic Krustpils ({{lang-de|Kreutzburg}}) lies on the right bank, in [[Latgale]]. The two cities were united during Soviet rule in 1962 under the J\u0113kabpils name, but retain their distinct regional character.\n\nJ\u0113kabpils was also formerly home to former Soviet [[J\u0113kabpils Air Base]].\n\n==History==\n\nA stone cross-castle&nbsp;\u2014 [[Krustpils Castle|Cruczeborch]] ({{lang-de|Kreutzburg}}) \u2013 was built in 1237 by the bishop of [[R\u012bga]]. Archeological excavations on the nearby Asote mound indicate that this place was a busy trading centre for the [[Latgalians]], one of the Latvian tribes, and had been inhabited since 1,000 BC. An adjoining settlement already existed when [[Krustpils Castle]] was first built; it grew up around the castle as the village of Krustpils. The village was often destroyed during local wars, such as Polish-Swedish battles, but was always rebuilt afterward.\n\nDuring the 17th century persecuted [[Old Believers]] from [[Russia]] settled along the Daugava river. In 1670 this settlement, gradually growing around the Sala Inn, became known as J\u0113kabpils ({{lang|de|Jakobstadt}} in German) in honor of the Duke of [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia|Courland]], [[Jacob Kettler]], who granted [[Magdeburg rights]] to the town.\n\nA local legend about the town's origin states that the duke was hunting one day but became lost. At the Daugava River he simultaneously spotted a lynx underneath a fir tree as well as a town at the same time. This image of the lynx underneath a fir tree is the town's [[coat of arms]].\n\nIn the period of the Duchy of Courland the residents of the town were mostly Russian Old believers, [[Poles]] and [[Lithuanians]]. Duke Jacob built a small port in the town to transport goods from a nearby iron foundry. At the end of 17th. century there were an anchor mint, a gun [[foundry]], lime and [[tar kiln]]s and several other factories in Jacobstadt.\nIn 1704, during the [[Great Northern War]], the town was occupied by the Russians. However, after few months a major battle, the ([[Battle of J\u0113kabpils]]), took place near the town. A [[Swedish Empire|Swedish]] army under [[Adam Ludwig Lewenhaupt|Adam Lewenhaupt]] defeated a much larger Russian force and thus stopped [[Russian Empire]] from further invasion in the Duchy.\nAfter the war and an epidemic of plague, the town again prospered. [[Barges]] from [[Belarus]] imported grain, honey, tobacco, spirits, textiles etc. At the same time land transport from [[Jaunjelgava|Friedrichstadt]] amounted to approx. 9000 cart loads a year during second half of the 18th century. Jacobstadt was also part of the postal road from [[Jelgava]] to Friedrichstadt and further to [[Il\u016bkste]].\nIn 1764 the first ferry crossing to Krustpils was opened in the town. During the reign of [[Peter von Biron]] a small community of German-speaking craftsmen developed in the town besides Russians and Poles.  [[Jews]], however, were prohibited from entering the town. In 1795 Jacobstadt, like the whole Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, was incorporated into the Russian Empire.\n\nIn 1826 [[Friedrich Georg Wilhelm von Struve]] made his geodesic measurements near the town.\nIn 1834 the first hospital was opened in the town. During this period a theater and library were also opened and the first streets were cobbled.\nIn 1861 with the opening of the [[Riga\u2013Daugavpils Railway|Riga\u2013Daugavpils railway]] through Krustpils the role of the Daugava and barges as a main means of transport decreased. However the river was still used for [[timber rafting]].\n\nAt the turn of the 20th century there were a bank, an insurance company, a match factory, a [[steam mill]], a [[brewery]], [[typography]] and several other enterprises. During the [[First World War]] heavy battles were fought around the town and some 280 buildings in the town were destroyed or damaged.\n\nIn 1919 J\u0113kabpils became the administrative centre of the newly established Jaunjelgava district. In 1932 a [[sugar refinery]] was built in the town. In 1936 a bridge was built over the Daugava. In this way J\u0113kabpils and Krustpils were united for the first time.\nDuring the [[Second World War]] the bridge was blown up. A new bridge was constructed only in 1962.\n\nJ\u0113kabpils and Krustpils were merged in 1962 under the name J\u0113kabpils. During the [[Latvian SSR|Soviet period]] the united city was home to several big factories. Among them were the sewing enterprise ''Asote'', the [[Dolomite (rock)|dolomite]] splinter mine ''Dolom\u012bts'', a [[reinforced concrete]] construction factory, a dairy processing plant and several other enterprises.\nAfter the restoration of Latvian independence in 1991 many factories went bankrupt or production was drastically reduced.\n\n==Geography==\n\nThe population of J\u0113kabpils town is 29,100. The two historical parts of J\u0113kabpils&nbsp;\u2014 Krustpils and historic J\u0113kabpils&nbsp;\u2014 are connected by the bridge across the [[Daugava River]].\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of 1 January 2017, the city had a population of 23,750.\n{{bar box\n|width = 300px\n|float = left\n|title = Demographics of J\u0113kabpils in 2017 population census <ref>[http://data.csb.gov.lv/Dialog/varval.asp?ma=TSG11-061&ti=TSG11%2D061%2E+PAST%C2V%CEGIE+IEDZ%CEVOT%C2JI+PA+STATISTISKAJIEM+RE%CCIONIEM%2C+REPUBLIKAS+PILS%C7T%C2M++UN+NOVADIEM+P%C7C+TAUT%CEBAS%2C+DZIMUMA+UN+PA+DZIM%D0ANAS+VALST%CEM+2011%2EGADA+1%2EMART%C2&path=../DATABASE/tautassk_11/2011.gada%20tautas%20skait%EE%F0anas%20gal%EEgie%20rezult%E2ti/&lang=16]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|titlebar = #ddd\n|bars =\n{{bar percent|Latvians|black|60.6}}\n{{bar percent|Russians|yellow|26.7}}\n{{bar percent|Belarusians|violet|3.1}}\n{{bar percent|Poles|red|2.9}}\n{{bar percent|Ukrainians|blue|1.8}}\n{{bar percent|Others|purple|5.0}}\n}}\n{{clear|left}}\n\n==Sights==\n\n===J\u0113kabpils===\nIn the older parts of the city, some buildings have been preserved. \nThe castle of [[Krustpils]] houses the History Museum of J\u0113kabpils and Krustpils.\n\n===J\u0113kabpils District===\nOne of the [[Struve Geodetic Arc]] original station points is located in ''Str\u016bves park''. In [[:lv:Tadenava|Tadenava]], not far from J\u0113kabpils itself, there is a memorial museum to the great Latvian poet [[Rainis]]. Nearby are also the castle of Justine and Dign\u0101ja. The highest point of [[Selonia]] \u2014 ''Orma\u0146kalns'' is in the vicinity of [[:lv:Klauce|Klauce]]. Between [[Nereta]] and [[Akn\u012bste]] there is a museum \"Rieksti\u0146i\" commemorating the famous Latvian writer [[J\u0101nis Jaunsudrabi\u0146\u0161]].\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Reinis Niti\u0161s]], [[FIA World Rallycross Championship|World Rallycross]] driver\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Latvia}}\n\nJ\u0113kabpils is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Starptautisk\u0101 sadarb\u012bba|url=https://www.jekabpils.lv/lv/pilseta/starptautiska-sadarbiba|website=jekabspils.lv|publisher=J\u0113kabpils|language=lv|accessdate=2019-08-31}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Czerwionka-Leszczyny]], Poland\n*{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Lida]], Belarus\n*{{flagicon|EST}} [[Maardu]], Estonia \n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Melle, Germany|Melle]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Myrhorod]], Ukraine\n*{{flagicon|AZE}} [[Qara\u00e7uxur]], Azerbaijan\n*{{flagicon|LTU}} [[Roki\u0161kis]], Lithuania\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Soko\u0142\u00f3w Podlaski]], Poland\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Jekabpils city council.JPG|J\u0113kabpils city council\nFile:Old believers church Jekabpils.JPG|Old believers church in J\u0113kabpils\nFile:\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0446\u0435\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044c (2).jpg|J\u0113kaba street and Holy Spirit Monastery elements\nFile:Oldtown square Jekabpils.JPG|J\u0113kabpils central square\nFile:Krustpils train station.(1)..JPG|Krustpils railway station in J\u0113kabpils\nFile:Krustpils palace (1).jpg|[[Krustpils Castle]]\nFile:J\u0113kabpils dam.jpg|P\u013cavi\u0146u iela (street) and Daugava River levee\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Latvian municipalities 2009}}\n{{Latvian regional cities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jekabplis}}\n[[Category:J\u0113kabpils| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Republican cities of Latvia]]\n", "name_user": "Ymblanter", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C4%93kabpils"}
{"title_page": "Zhanna Shapialevich", "text_new": "{{short description|Belarusian sport shooter}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = Zhanna Shapialevich\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Zhanna Henadziyeuna Shitsik-<br>Shapialevich\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = {{BLR}}\n| residence      =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|2|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hrodna]], [[Belarusian SSR]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.64|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|63|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Shooting sport|Shooting]]\n| event          = 10 m air pistol ([[AP40]])<br>25 m pistol ([[25 metre pistol|SP]]) \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = SK VS Hrodna<ref name=issf/> \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = Aleh Pishchukevich<ref name=issf/> \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Zhanna Henadziyeuna Shapialevich''' ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] '''Shitsik''') ({{lang-be|\u0416\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0435\u045e\u043d\u0430 \u0428\u044b\u0446\u0456\u043a-\u0428\u0430\u043f\u044f\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0447}}; born February 26, 1971 in [[Hrodna]]) is a Belarusian sport shooter.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Zhanna Shapialevich|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sh/zhanna-shitik-shepelevich-1.html|20 January 2013}}</ref> Shapialevich made her official debut for the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], where she placed fourteenth in the [[Shooting at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 25 metre pistol|women's 25 m pistol]], accumulating a score of 577 points.<ref name=issf>{{cite web|title=ISSF Profile \u2013 Zhanna Shapialevich|url=http://www.issf-sports.org/athletes/athlete.ashx?personissfid=SHBLRW2602197101|publisher=[[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]]|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nTwelve years after competing in her last Olympics, Shapialevich qualified for her second Belarusian team, as a 37-year-old, at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], by finishing eighth in the sport pistol from the [[2006 ISSF World Shooting Championships]] in [[Zagreb, Croatia]].<ref name=issf/> She placed forty-second out of forty-four shooters in the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Women's 10 metre air pistol|women's 10 m air pistol]] by one point ahead of Uruguay's [[Carolina Lozado]], with a total score of 368 targets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 10m Air Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHW203901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |accessdate=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816052426/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHW203901/index.html |archivedate=16 August 2012 }}</ref> Three days later, Shapialevich competed for her second event, [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 25 metre pistol|25 m pistol]], where she was able to shoot 287 targets in the precision stage, and 282 in the rapid fire, for a total score of 569 points, finishing only in thirty-eighth place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 25m Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHW204902/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |accessdate=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816053058/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHW204902/index.html |archivedate=16 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=62987/bio/index.html NBC 2008 Olympics profile] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapialevich, Zhanna}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Belarusian female sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Belarus]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Grodno]]\n\n\n{{Belarus-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belarusian sport shooter}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = Zhanna Shapialevich\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Zhanna Henadziyeuna Shitsik-<br>Shapialevich\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = {{BLR}}\n| residence      =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1971|2|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hrodna]], [[Belarusian SSR]]\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.64|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|63|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Shooting sport|Shooting]]\n| event          = 10 m air pistol ([[AP40]])<br>25 m pistol ([[25 metre pistol|SP]]) \n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = SK VS Hrodna<ref name=issf/> \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          = Aleh Pishchukevich<ref name=issf/> \n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Zhanna Henadziyeuna Shapialevich''' ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] '''Shitsik''') ({{lang-be|\u0416\u0430\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0435\u045e\u043d\u0430 \u0428\u044b\u0446\u0456\u043a-\u0428\u0430\u043f\u044f\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0456\u0447}}; born February 26, 1971 in [[Hrodna]]) is a Belarusian sport shooter.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Zhanna Shapialevich|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/sh/zhanna-shitik-shepelevich-1.html|20 January 2013}}</ref> Shapialevich made her official debut for the [[1996 Summer Olympics]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], where she placed fourteenth in the [[Shooting at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 25 metre pistol|women's 25 m pistol]], accumulating a score of 577 points.<ref name=issf>{{cite web|title=ISSF Profile \u2013 Zhanna Shapialevich|url=http://www.issf-sports.org/athletes/athlete.ashx?personissfid=SHBLRW2602197101|publisher=[[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]]|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nTwelve years after competing in her last Olympics, Shapialevich qualified for her second Belarusian team, as a 37-year-old, at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], by finishing eighth in the sport pistol from the [[2006 ISSF World Shooting Championships]] in [[Zagreb, Croatia]].<ref name=issf/> She placed forty-second out of forty-four shooters in the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Women's 10 metre air pistol|women's 10 m air pistol]] by one point ahead of Uruguay's [[Carolina Lozado]], with a total score of 368 targets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 10m Air Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHW203901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |accessdate=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816052426/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHW203901/index.html |archivedate=16 August 2012 }}</ref> Three days later, Shapialevich competed for her second event, [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 25 metre pistol|25 m pistol]], where she was able to shoot 287 targets in the precision stage, and 282 in the rapid fire, for a total score of 569 points, finishing only in thirty-eighth place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 25m Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHW204902/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |accessdate=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816053058/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHW204902/index.html |archivedate=16 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=62987/bio/index.html NBC Olympics Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shapialevich, Zhanna}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Belarusian female sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Belarus]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Grodno]]\n\n\n{{Belarus-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "tag dead link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhanna_Shapialevich"}
{"title_page": "Kyle Davis (table tennis)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian table tennis player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox table tennis player\n| name           = Kyle Davis \n| image          = KyleDavis.jpg\n| imagesize      = 200px\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Kyle Davis \n| nickname       = ''Rooner''<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| nationality    = {{AUS}}\n| residence      =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1989|1|18}}\n| birth_place    = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.78|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|74|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| playingstyle   = Right-handed, classic<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| equipment      = Butterfly Jonyer<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| club           = Melbourne Sports and<br>Aquatic Centre<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| hrank          = 401 (December 2008)<ref name=wr/>\n| crank          = 473 (October 2011)<ref name=wr/>\n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''Kyle Davis''' (born 18 January 1989, in [[Melbourne]]) is an Australian table tennis player.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Kyle Davis|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/da/kyle-davis-1.html|21 October 2014}}</ref> He was selected to represent his nation, Australia, at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] and at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Delhi, India]]. As of October 2011, Davis is ranked no. 401 in the world by the [[International Table Tennis Federation]] (ITTF).<ref name=wr>{{cite web|title=ITTF World Ranking \u2013 Kyle Davis|url=http://www.ittf.com/ittf_ranking/world_ranking_per_name.asp?Player_ID=102113|publisher=[[International Table Tennis Federation|ITTF]]|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref> He is also right-handed, and uses the classic grip and Butterfly Jonyer blade.<ref name=tt-bio>{{cite web|title=ITTF World Player Profile \u2013 Kyle Davis|url=http://www.ittf.com/biography/biography_web_details.asp?Player_ID=102113|publisher=[[International Table Tennis Federation|ITTF]]|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nSince becoming a member of the national team in 2004, Davis is considered one of Australia's most promising table tennis players in its sporting history. He has obtained thirty-six age-group Australian titles in both the singles and doubles tournaments, and finished fourth in the men's doubles at the Australian Youth Olympic Festival.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kyle Davis \u2013 Table Tennis|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/scholarships/scholarship-profile/?scholarshipID=17|publisher=[[Sport Australia Hall of Fame Awards|Sport Australia Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref> In 2007, Davis picked up a silver medal at the peak of his career in the men's singles at the Commonwealth Championships in [[Jaipur, India]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Marshall|first=Ian|title=Top Seeds to Meet in Men's Team Final at Commonwealth Championships|url=http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?Year=&General_Catigory=&ID=11814&Category=&Competition_ID=&Player_ID=101439&|publisher=[[International Table Tennis Federation|ITTF]]|date=1 June 2007|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nDavis qualified for the Australian squad, as a 19-year-old teen, in two table tennis events at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in Beijing, by placing second in the men's singles from the Oceania Qualification Tournament in [[Noumea]], and receiving a continental spot for Oceania in the men's team under ITTF's Computer Team Ranking List.<ref>{{cite web|title=Players Qualified for the Olympic Games |url=http://www.ittf.com/World_Events/Olympic_games_2008/Olympics_08_players_list_Final_28_Jul_2008.pdf |format=[[PDF]] |publisher=[[International Table Tennis Federation|ITTF]] |accessdate=26 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815012958/http://ittf.com/World_Events/Olympic_games_2008/Olympics_08_players_list_Final_28_Jul_2008.pdf |archivedate=15 August 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Marshall|first=Ian|title=Emotional Scenes as Australians Secure Olympic Places in New Caledonia|url=http://www.ittf.com/_front_page/ittf_full_story1.asp?ID=15183&Competition_ID=1700&|publisher=[[International Table Tennis Federation|ITTF]]|date=7 April 2008|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref> Joining his fellow players [[William Henzell]] and [[David Zalcberg]] in the inaugural [[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team|men's team]] event, Davis and his Australian squad finished on the bottom of the prelim pool with three straight defeats against Greece, Austria, and the host nation China.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's Team Group A (AUS\u2013GRE)|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/tabletennis/resultsandschedules/rsc=TTM400A06/index.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=25 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120821153602/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/tabletennis/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DTTM400A06/index.html|archive-date=21 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=No joy for Aussie table tennis teams|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/08/14/2335978.htm?site=olympics/2008|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC News Australia]]|date=14 August 2008|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref> A few days later, in the [[Table tennis at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's singles|men's singles]], Davis lost his opening match to Egypt's [[Ahmed Saleh (table tennis)|Ahmed Ali Saleh]] with a set score 1\u20134.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's Singles Preliminary Round|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/tabletennis/resultsandschedules/rsc=TTM001912/index.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=26 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Paxinos|first=Stathi|title=Miao Miao progresses in table tennis|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/table-tennis/miao-miao-progresses-in-table-tennis/2008/08/19/1218911707899.html|publisher=[[The Age]]|date=19 August 2008|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=South Korean paddler challenged in men's singles at Beijing Olympics|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-08/20/content_9552045.htm|publisher=[[The Age]]|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ITTF|102113}}\n* [http://corporate.olympics.com.au/athlete/kyle-davis Australian Olympic Team Bio]\n* [http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=65337/bio/index.html NBC 2008 Olympics profile] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Kyle}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Table tennis players at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Olympic table tennis players of Australia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Melbourne]]\n\n\n{{Australia-sport-bio-stub}}\n{{tabletennis-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian table tennis player|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox table tennis player\n| name           = Kyle Davis \n| image          = KyleDavis.jpg\n| imagesize      = 200px\n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = Kyle Davis \n| nickname       = ''Rooner''<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| nationality    = {{AUS}}\n| residence      =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1989|1|18}}\n| birth_place    = [[Melbourne]], Australia\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.78|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|74|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| playingstyle   = Right-handed, classic<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| equipment      = Butterfly Jonyer<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| club           = Melbourne Sports and<br>Aquatic Centre<ref name=tt-bio/>\n| hrank          = 401 (December 2008)<ref name=wr/>\n| crank          = 473 (October 2011)<ref name=wr/>\n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals   